title: Study of excitation function of deuteron induced reactions on natKr up to 20 MeV

x4freetext: Study of excitation function of deuteron induced
reactions on natKr up to 20 MeV

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Applied Radiation and Isotopes, Vol.70, p.574 (2012)

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4freetext: Natural krypton gas.
Stacked gas cell
targets. Kapton (15 micron thick polyimide foil)
window. Ti (12 and 21 microns) and Fe (12 microns)
foils were inserted in front of the stacks for beam
intensity monitoring. The activity of each cell was
determined without chemical separation via standard
high-resolution gamma-ray spectroscopy. The sources
were counted at large distances from the detector to
be able to handle the gas cells as point sources.
Beam intensity was 60-150 nA to avoid considerable
density reduction.

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: Nuclear Data Services (Doc. series of NDS), No.1211 (2001)

x4freetext: Chapter 4
The initial beam uncertainty was +-0.3 MeV and
+- 0.2 MeV in Brussels and in Debrecen respectively.
The uncertainty of the beam energy in the
middle of each irradiated cell was estimated
combining the uncertainties of the energy degradation
depending on the pressure of the gas and the thickness
of the window and monitor foils.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The overall uncertainty amounted to 12-20%.
incident charged particle flux (8%),
energy dependent detector efficiency (5%),
effective target thickness (5%),
nuclear decay and branching data (3%),
statistical and peak fitting (1-7%),
The uncertainty of the cross-sections were
estimated taking the independent relative errors of the
linearly contributing components.
The experimental data were compared to the
results of the theoretical model codes TALYS, EPIRE-D
and ALICE-D.
Fitted excitation functions were used for
determination of integral physical yields.
